#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:169
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Internet dial-up configuration\n"
"------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:175
msgid ""
"The \"offline\" flag in chrony.conf prevents chronyd from trying to query "
"the time service when the computer is not connected to the Internet. To "
"switch to 'online' when connected, add these lines to /etc/ppp/ip-up or "
"whatever script takes you online:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:180
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    /usr/bin/chronyc << EOF\n"
"    password [keyword]\n"
"    online\n"
"    EOF\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:183
msgid ""
"To return to the offline state when disconnecting, add these lines to "
"/etc/ppp/ip-down (or equivalent script):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:190
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    /usr/bin/chronyc << EOF\n"
"    password [keyword]\n"
"    dump\n"
"    writertc\n"
"    offline\n"
"    EOF\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:192
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The driftfile\n"
"-------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:199
msgid ""
"One of the main activities of the 'chronyd' program is to work out the rate "
"at which the system clock gains or loses relative to real time. Every time "
"this rate information is computed, it is recorded in the driftfile "
"/etc/chrony.drift. Data in the driftfile looks something like:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:202
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"    $ cat /etc/chrony.drift\n"
"           14.6433               1.2223\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:206
msgid ""
"The first number is the rate at which the system clock gains or loses time "
"in parts-per-million. The second rate is an estimate of the error bound "
"around the first value in which the true rate actually lies."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:208
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Synchronizing the hardware clock (RTC)\n"
"--------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:217
msgid ""
"The computer relies on the real-time clock (RTC) to maintain the correct "
"time during shutdown and offline periods. At boot up, chronyd sets the "
"system time to RTC time. When the Internet connection is made, chronyd "
"starts measuring the error and drift rate between system and RTC time, "
"gradually bring both times into sync with the NTP time signal. After a "
"number of hours online, both system time and RTC time will equal true time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/chrony_time.txt:223
msgid ""
"My LFS system used a 'setclock' boot script to set system time to the "
"resl-time clock. Since chronyd now fulfills this function, I removed "
"'setclock' from the boot process. Any program other than chronyd that "
"adjusts the real-time clock can confuse the time synchronization process."
msgstr ""

